layout: layouts/base-finpay.njk
title: "Self-Directed Brokerage Account (SDBA) Management | Capital Wealth"
description: "Professional SDBA management for your 401(k) or TSP. Access 5,000+ mutual funds with expert guidance. Fiduciary advisor in Lehi, Utah. Free consultation."
breadcrumbs:
  - { name: "Home", url: "/" }
  - { name: "Services", url: "/services/" }
  - { name: "SDBA", url: "/services/sdba/" }
faqSchema:
  - question: "What is a Self-Directed Brokerage Account?"
    answer: "An SDBA is a feature within your employer retirement plan (401k, 403b, 457, or TSP) that lets you invest in thousands of mutual funds and ETFs beyond the standard fund lineup. Think of it as a brokerage window inside your retirement plan."
  - question: "Does my plan offer an SDBA?"
    answer: "Many large employers and the federal TSP offer brokerage windows. Check with your plan administrator or HR department — or contact us and we'll help you find out."
  - question: "What plans typically offer SDBAs?"
    answer: "Many large employers offer SDBAs through platforms like Fidelity BrokerageLink, Schwab Personal Choice Retirement Account (PCRA), or Vanguard. Check with your plan administrator or HR department — or contact us and we'll help you find out."
  - question: "How much does an SDBA cost?"
    answer: "Typical costs include an annual maintenance fee ($28.75-$50/year is common), fund expense ratios (varies by fund), and potential trading fees. We analyze all costs to ensure your SDBA makes financial sense."
  - question: "Is an SDBA right for everyone?"
    answer: "No. If your core plan lineup has strong, low-cost index funds and you're well-diversified, an SDBA may not add enough value to justify the fees. We'll evaluate your situation honestly — even if it means telling you don't need one."
  - question: "Can my financial advisor manage my SDBA?"
    answer: "Yes — that's exactly what we do. Most advisors can't access your workplace plan. An SDBA creates a bridge that lets us professionally manage your retirement plan investments alongside your other accounts."
  - question: "What's the minimum balance for an SDBA?"
    answer: "It varies by plan. Corporate plans vary — some have no minimum, others require $5,000-$10,000. Contact your plan administrator or we can help you determine your plan's specific requirements."
  - question: "How is this different from just rolling over to an IRA?"
    answer: "With an SDBA, your money stays in your employer plan (which may have institutional pricing, creditor protection, and unique loan provisions). A rollover removes the money entirely. Both have pros and cons — we help you decide which is better."
