   6. FAQ — Editorial accordion
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">SDBA FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Everything you need to know about Self-Directed Brokerage Accounts and professional management.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Ask About SDBAs</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is a Self-Directed Brokerage Account? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>An SDBA is a feature within your employer retirement plan (401k, 403b, 457, or TSP) that lets you invest in thousands of mutual funds and ETFs beyond the standard fund lineup. Think of it as a brokerage window inside your retirement plan.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Does my plan offer an SDBA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Many large employers and the federal TSP offer brokerage windows. Check with your plan administrator or HR department — or contact us and we'll help you find out.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What plans typically offer SDBAs? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Many large employers offer SDBAs through platforms like Fidelity BrokerageLink, Schwab Personal Choice Retirement Account (PCRA), or Vanguard. Check with your plan administrator or HR department — or contact us and we'll help you find out.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How much does an SDBA cost? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Typical costs include an annual maintenance fee ($28.75-$50/year is common), fund expense ratios (varies by fund), and potential trading fees. We analyze all costs to ensure your SDBA makes financial sense.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Is an SDBA right for everyone? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>No. If your core plan lineup has strong, low-cost index funds and you're well-diversified, an SDBA may not add enough value to justify the fees. We'll evaluate your situation honestly — even if it means telling you don't need one.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can my financial advisor manage my SDBA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes — that's exactly what we do. Most advisors can't access your workplace plan. An SDBA creates a bridge that lets us professionally manage your retirement plan investments alongside your other accounts.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What's the minimum balance for an SDBA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>It varies by plan. Corporate plans vary — some have no minimum, others require $5,000-$10,000. Contact your plan administrator or we can help you determine your plan's specific requirements.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How is this different from just rolling over to an IRA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>With an SDBA, your money stays in your employer plan (which may have institutional pricing, creditor protection, and unique loan provisions). A rollover removes the money entirely. Both have pros and cons — we help you decide which is better.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

